A — Analysing
Once you have numbers, you'll almost certainly find one of these three culprits:
The DHT22 read is the most likely stall. It runs on the main thread with a blocking dht.temperature call, and it can take 20–50ms when the sensor hiccups. That's longer than your entire time.sleep(0.02) loop budget.
safe_stats() is called every single cycle and computes 11 statistics across multiple arrays. On a Pi Zero/3, repeated np.percentile, np.polyfit, and np.std on 250-element arrays add up fast.
The Isolation Forest decision_function() runs all estimators on every cycle. If your model was exported with the default 100 estimators, that's 100 tree traversals per loop.

S — Scheduling
This is the biggest win for your lag problem specifically. Move the DHT22 read off the main thread entirely:
pythonimport threading

_dht_lock  = threading.Lock()
_dht_temp  = None

def _dht_reader():
    global _dht_temp
    while True:
        try:
            t = dht.temperature
            if t is not None:
                with _dht_lock:
                    _dht_temp = float(t)
        except RuntimeError:
            pass
        time.sleep(2.0)

threading.Thread(target=_dht_reader, daemon=True).start()

# In main loop — non-blocking, just read the cached value:
with _dht_lock:
    amb_t = _dht_temp
This means a slow DHT22 read never stalls the inference loop. The temperature value is always at most 2 seconds stale, which is fine since you're already using it as environmental context, not a real-time signal.
Also add a scheduling gate — skip Stage 2 feature extraction entirely when contact_status != "GOOD", which you already do, but also skip safe_stats() and the full feature vector build on those cycles. Those are currently computed unconditionally every loop.

O — Optimisation
Three concrete optimisations for the rubric, ordered by effort:
1. Float32 quantization on the feature pipeline — your safe_stats() already casts to float32 for the array, but the intermediate Python float() conversions and pd.DataFrame creation use float64. The bigger win is pre-allocating a numpy array instead of building a dict then a DataFrame every cycle:
